<DOC><DOCNO> AP890706-0013 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 0036EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather 2ndLd-Writethru a0728</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0728,0401</SECOND><HEAD>Storm Dumps Heavy Rain on East Coast; Southwest Still Hot</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 1, 4 and 6 with one graf each to CORRECT with revisedweather service figures for New Jersey.</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Heavy rain drenched the East Coast on Wednesday, causingwidespread flooding with eight inches of rain in New Jersey, and 10inches in Maryland.   The heat continued in the desert Southwest, where temperaturesnear 110 degrees were recorded in parts of Arizona and California.   Showers stretched along the Atlantic Coast from the Carolinas toNew York. Two people, including a 9-year-old boy, drowned and morethan 450 people were evacuated because of flooding in northernDelaware.   Salem County, N.J., was deluged with eight inches of rain andsouthern Anne Arundel County, Md., had 10 inches. The NationalWeather Service initially reported 20 inches fell in southeasternBucks County, Pa., and in the Philadelphia area, but revised thatreport to 2.8 inches. It also revised lower an initial report of 13inches of rain in Monroe, N.J.   Heavy rain flooded tracks and disrupted Amtrak passenger servicealong the railroad's busy northeast corridor. Busing and long delaysaffected nearly 10,000 passengers, a spokesman said.   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDTincluded 6.28 inches at Mt. Holly, N.J.; 5.7 inches at Wrightstown,N.J.; 4.8 inches at downtown Philadelphia; 2.3 inches at Newark,N.J.; 1.5 inches at Wilmington, Del.; and 1.2 inches at New YorkCity's Kennedy Airport.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 57degrees at Arcata Crescent City, Calif., to 112 degrees at Pierre,S.D. Wednesday's low in the Lower 48 states was 26 degrees atTruckee, Calif.   Thursday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from themiddle and south Atlantic Coast states, the Ohio and Tennesseevalleys, the Gulf Coast states to southern and eastern Texas; andwidely scattered thunderstorms across northern Minnesota, northwestWisconsin and western upper Michigan.   Highs were predicted in the 70s over western Washington and alongmuch of the Pacific Coast; 80s to lower 90s across most of thenation; between 95 and 105 degrees from the central Plains to SouthDakota and southern Minnesota; 95 to 105 degrees over the GreatBasin and interior valleys of California, New Mexico and southwestTexas; and between 105 to 120 degrees in the desert Southwest.</TEXT></DOC>